    {"id": 1, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is B.Tech?", "answer": "B.Tech (Bachelor of Technology) is a four-year undergraduate engineering degree focused on applied, hands-on technical training. It mixes core science subjects, programming, labs, and a specialization stream like CSE, AI, or ECE."},
    {"id": 2, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is B.Tech in AI and Data Science?", "answer": "It's a specialization within B.Tech that focuses on machine learning, deep learning, data analysis, statistics, and AI systems, on top of the usual core computer science subjects like programming and DSA."},
    {"id": 3, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is the difference between B.Tech and B.E.?", "answer": "Both are four-year engineering degrees and are treated as equivalent in India. B.Tech tends to lean more practical and skill-based, while B.E. historically leaned more theoretical, but in practice the curricula overlap heavily today."},
    {"id": 4, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What subjects are covered in B.Tech CSE first year?", "answer": "First year usually covers engineering mathematics, physics or chemistry, a programming language (commonly C or Python), basic electronics, and an introduction to computing or problem solving — building the foundation for core CS subjects later."},
    {"id": 5, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is the difference between CSE and AI/ML specialization?", "answer": "CSE gives a broad computer science foundation covering DSA, OS, networks, and databases. An AI/ML specialization keeps that core but replaces some electives with focused courses in machine learning, deep learning, and data science."},
    {"id": 6, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is a credit system in B.Tech?", "answer": "Each course is assigned credit points based on weekly teaching hours. You need a minimum total credit count across semesters to graduate, and your grade in each course is weighted by its credits to calculate your GPA."},
    {"id": 7, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is an internship and why is it important during B.Tech?", "answer": "An internship is short-term, supervised work experience at a company, usually done between semesters or in the final year. It gives practical exposure, helps build a resume, and often leads directly to placement offers."},
    {"id": 8, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is the eligibility for B.Tech admission?", "answer": "Typically a student needs to have completed 12th grade with Physics, Chemistry, and Mathematics, and qualify through an entrance exam such as JEE Main, a state-level CET, or a university's own test, depending on the institute."},
    {"id": 9, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is a minor project vs major project in B.Tech?", "answer": "A minor project is usually a smaller, single-semester project done in an earlier year to practice applying concepts. A major project is a larger final-year project, often spanning two semesters, that's meant to showcase deeper technical skill."},
    {"id": 10, "category": "B.Tech & Engineering", "question": "What is the scope of B.Tech AI graduates?", "answer": "Graduates can work as ML engineers, data scientists, AI researchers, data analysts, or software developers, across industries like tech, finance, healthcare, and e-commerce. Many also pursue an M.Tech or MS for research-focused roles."},
    {"id": 11, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is Artificial Intelligence (AI)?", "answer": "AI is the field of building systems that can perform tasks which normally require human intelligence, such as recognizing images, understanding language, making decisions, or learning from data."},
    {"id": 12, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What are the types of AI?", "answer": "AI is often grouped into Narrow AI (built for one specific task, like spam filtering), General AI (a hypothetical system with human-level reasoning across any task), and Super AI (a theoretical AI surpassing human intelligence)."},
    {"id": 13, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is the Turing Test?", "answer": "Proposed by Alan Turing, it's a test of whether a machine's conversation is indistinguishable from a human's. If a human judge can't reliably tell the machine apart from a person through text conversation, the machine is said to pass."},
    {"id": 14, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is the difference between AI, ML and Deep Learning?", "answer": "AI is the broad goal of making machines act intelligently. Machine Learning is a subset of AI where systems learn patterns from data instead of following fixed rules. Deep Learning is a subset of ML that uses multi-layered neural networks for that learning."},
    {"id": 15, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What are intelligent agents in AI?", "answer": "An intelligent agent perceives its environment through sensors and acts on it through actuators to achieve a goal — think of a thermostat, a self-driving car's controller, or a chatbot, each sensing input and choosing an action."},
    {"id": 16, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is knowledge representation in AI?", "answer": "It's the way an AI system stores facts about the world so it can reason with them — common forms include logic statements, semantic networks, rules (if-then), and frames or ontologies."},
    {"id": 17, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is heuristic search in AI?", "answer": "Heuristic search uses a rule-of-thumb estimate (the heuristic) to decide which path looks most promising, letting an algorithm find a good solution faster without exploring every possible option."},
    {"id": 18, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is the A* algorithm?", "answer": "A* is a pathfinding and graph search algorithm that combines the actual cost to reach a node with a heuristic estimate of the remaining cost to the goal, letting it find the shortest path efficiently. It's widely used in games and robotics navigation."},
    {"id": 19, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is an expert system?", "answer": "An expert system is an early style of AI program that mimics decision-making of a human expert using a large base of if-then rules, commonly used in fields like medical diagnosis or technical troubleshooting."},
    {"id": 20, "category": "Artificial Intelligence", "question": "What is Generative AI?", "answer": "Generative AI refers to models that create new content — text, images, audio, or code — rather than just classifying or predicting existing data. Large language models and image diffusion models are common examples."},
    {"id": 21, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is Machine Learning?", "answer": "Machine Learning is a branch of AI where algorithms learn patterns directly from data and improve their performance over time, instead of being explicitly programmed with fixed rules for every case."},
    {"id": 22, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is supervised learning?", "answer": "Supervised learning trains a model on labeled data — input-output pairs — so it learns to map new inputs to the correct output. Common tasks include classification (spam vs not spam) and regression (predicting a price)."},
    {"id": 23, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is unsupervised learning?", "answer": "Unsupervised learning works with unlabeled data, finding hidden structure or patterns on its own. Clustering (grouping similar customers) and dimensionality reduction are typical examples."},
    {"id": 24, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is reinforcement learning?", "answer": "Reinforcement learning trains an agent to make decisions by rewarding good actions and penalizing bad ones, letting it learn an optimal strategy through trial and error — used in robotics and game-playing AI like AlphaGo."},
    {"id": 25, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is overfitting and underfitting?", "answer": "Overfitting happens when a model learns the training data too closely, including its noise, and performs poorly on new data. Underfitting happens when a model is too simple to capture the real pattern, performing poorly even on training data."},
    {"id": 26, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is a confusion matrix?", "answer": "A confusion matrix is a table that compares a classification model's predictions against actual labels, showing true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives — used to calculate accuracy, precision, and recall."},
    {"id": 27, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is cross-validation?", "answer": "Cross-validation splits the data into multiple folds, training on some and testing on the rest in rotation, to get a more reliable estimate of how a model will perform on unseen data than a single train-test split."},
    {"id": 28, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is feature engineering?", "answer": "Feature engineering is the process of selecting, transforming, or creating input variables (features) from raw data so a machine learning model can learn patterns more effectively."},
    {"id": 29, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is gradient descent?", "answer": "Gradient descent is an optimization algorithm that repeatedly adjusts a model's parameters in the direction that reduces error the fastest, gradually moving toward the values that minimize the loss function."},
    {"id": 30, "category": "Machine Learning", "question": "What is the bias-variance tradeoff?", "answer": "Bias is error from overly simple assumptions (underfitting); variance is error from being too sensitive to training data (overfitting). Good models balance the two, since reducing one often increases the other."},
    {"id": 31, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is Deep Learning?", "answer": "Deep Learning is a subfield of machine learning that uses artificial neural networks with many layers to automatically learn complex patterns directly from raw data like images, audio, or text."},
    {"id": 32, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is a neural network?", "answer": "A neural network is a model made of layers of connected 'neurons,' loosely inspired by the brain, where each connection has a weight that's adjusted during training so the network learns to map inputs to outputs."},
    {"id": 33, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is backpropagation?", "answer": "Backpropagation is the algorithm used to train neural networks — it calculates how much each weight contributed to the error and adjusts the weights backward through the network to reduce that error, using gradient descent."},
    {"id": 34, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is a CNN (Convolutional Neural Network)?", "answer": "A CNN is a type of neural network designed for grid-like data such as images. It uses filters that slide across the input to detect local patterns like edges and textures, making it very effective for image recognition."},
    {"id": 35, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is an RNN/LSTM?", "answer": "An RNN (Recurrent Neural Network) processes sequences by feeding its own previous output back as input, making it suited for time series or text. An LSTM is a special type of RNN with gates that help it remember information over longer sequences."},
    {"id": 36, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is a Transformer model?", "answer": "A Transformer is a neural network architecture that uses a mechanism called self-attention to weigh the relevance of every part of the input to every other part, processing sequences in parallel. It's the basis for models like GPT and BERT."},
    {"id": 37, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is an activation function?", "answer": "An activation function decides whether and how strongly a neuron 'fires' by introducing non-linearity into the network. Common examples are ReLU, Sigmoid, and Tanh, and without them a neural network couldn't learn complex patterns."},
    {"id": 38, "category": "Deep Learning", "question": "What is dropout in neural networks?", "answer": "Dropout is a regularization technique where randomly chosen neurons are temporarily ignored during training, forcing the network to not rely too heavily on any single neuron — this helps reduce overfitting."},
    {"id": 39, "category": "NLP", "question": "What is Natural Language Processing (NLP)?", "answer": "NLP is the field of AI focused on enabling computers to understand, interpret, and generate human language, covering tasks like translation, sentiment analysis, summarization, and chatbots."},
    {"id": 40, "category": "NLP", "question": "What is tokenization in NLP?", "answer": "Tokenization is the process of breaking text into smaller units called tokens — usually words, subwords, or characters — which is typically the first step before any other NLP processing."},
    {"id": 41, "category": "NLP", "question": "What are word embeddings?", "answer": "Word embeddings are dense numerical vectors that represent words in a way that captures meaning — words used in similar contexts end up with similar vectors. Word2Vec and GloVe are classic examples."},
    {"id": 42, "category": "NLP", "question": "What is sentiment analysis?", "answer": "Sentiment analysis is an NLP task that determines the emotional tone behind text, typically classifying it as positive, negative, or neutral — commonly used to analyze reviews or social media posts."},
    {"id": 43, "category": "NLP", "question": "What is a large language model (LLM)?", "answer": "An LLM is a deep learning model, usually based on the Transformer architecture, trained on massive amounts of text to predict and generate language, enabling it to answer questions, write text, and hold conversations."},
    {"id": 44, "category": "NLP", "question": "What is the Universal Sentence Encoder?", "answer": "The Universal Sentence Encoder (USE) is a pretrained model that converts a sentence into a fixed-length numerical vector capturing its meaning, so that sentences with similar meaning end up with similar vectors — useful for semantic search and FAQ matching."},
    {"id": 45, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What programming language should a B.Tech AI student learn first?", "answer": "Python is usually the best starting point because of its simple syntax and huge ecosystem of AI/ML libraries. Learning core programming concepts in C alongside it also helps build a strong fundamentals base."},
    {"id": 46, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is Python and why is it popular for AI?", "answer": "Python is a high-level, easy-to-read programming language. It's popular for AI because of its simple syntax and a rich set of libraries like NumPy, Pandas, scikit-learn, TensorFlow, and PyTorch that handle the heavy lifting."},
    {"id": 47, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What are Python libraries used in AI/ML?", "answer": "Common ones include NumPy and Pandas for data handling, Matplotlib and Seaborn for visualization, scikit-learn for classical ML, and TensorFlow or PyTorch for deep learning."},
    {"id": 48, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is the difference between Python 2 and Python 3?", "answer": "Python 3 is the actively maintained version with improvements like better Unicode handling and `print()` as a function rather than a statement. Python 2 reached end-of-life in 2020, so all new projects should use Python 3."},
    {"id": 49, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is Java used for in B.Tech?", "answer": "Java is widely taught for its strong object-oriented design, platform independence, and use in enterprise software, Android app development, and large backend systems."},
    {"id": 50, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is the difference between Java and Python?", "answer": "Java is statically typed and compiled to bytecode, generally faster and stricter about types, while Python is dynamically typed and interpreted, favoring readability and faster development at some cost to raw speed."},
    {"id": 51, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is C used for in engineering?", "answer": "C is a foundational, low-level language used to teach core programming concepts like memory management and pointers. It's still widely used for operating systems, embedded systems, and performance-critical software."},
    {"id": 52, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is the difference between C and C++?", "answer": "C is a procedural language focused on functions and structured programming. C++ extends C with object-oriented features like classes and inheritance, plus added capabilities like templates and the standard template library."},
    {"id": 53, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is object-oriented programming (OOP)?", "answer": "OOP is a programming style that organizes code around 'objects' — bundles of data and behavior — making large programs easier to design, reuse, and maintain compared to writing one long sequence of instructions."},
    {"id": 54, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What are the four pillars of OOP?", "answer": "The four pillars are encapsulation (bundling data and methods together), abstraction (hiding implementation details), inheritance (reusing behavior from a parent class), and polymorphism (treating different types through a common interface)."},
    {"id": 55, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is JavaScript used for?", "answer": "JavaScript is the core scripting language of the web, used to make webpages interactive on the frontend, and with Node.js it's also used to build backend servers and APIs."},
    {"id": 56, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is the difference between JavaScript and Java despite the similar name?", "answer": "Aside from the name, they're unrelated. Java is a statically typed, compiled, general-purpose language often used for backend and Android apps, while JavaScript is a dynamically typed scripting language built primarily for the web."},
    {"id": 57, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is the R programming language used for?", "answer": "R is a language built specifically for statistics and data analysis, popular in academic research and statistical modeling, with strong built-in support for plotting and data visualization."},
    {"id": 58, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is SQL?", "answer": "SQL (Structured Query Language) is used to create, query, update, and manage data stored in relational databases, using commands like SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE."},
    {"id": 59, "category": "Programming Languages", "question": "What is the difference between compiled and interpreted languages?", "answer": "A compiled language (like C++) is translated entirely into machine code before running, which is usually fast. An interpreted language (like Python) is executed line-by-line by an interpreter at runtime, which is usually slower but more flexible."},
    {"id": 60, "category": "DSA", "question": "What are data structures?", "answer": "Data structures are organized ways of storing and managing data so it can be accessed and modified efficiently — common examples include arrays, linked lists, stacks, queues, trees, and graphs."},
    {"id": 61, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is the difference between an array and a linked list?", "answer": "An array stores elements in contiguous memory with fast index-based access but a fixed or costly-to-resize size. A linked list stores elements as nodes connected by pointers, making insertion and deletion easier but access slower since you must traverse from the start."},
    {"id": 62, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is a stack and where is it used?", "answer": "A stack is a Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) data structure where the most recently added element is the first removed. It's used for things like undo functionality, function call management, and expression evaluation."},
    {"id": 63, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is a queue?", "answer": "A queue is a First-In-First-Out (FIFO) data structure where elements are added at the back and removed from the front, commonly used for task scheduling and handling requests in order."},
    {"id": 64, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is a binary search tree?", "answer": "A binary search tree is a tree where each node has at most two children, and for every node, all values in the left subtree are smaller and all values in the right subtree are larger — enabling efficient searching, insertion, and deletion."},
    {"id": 65, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is time complexity and Big-O notation?", "answer": "Time complexity describes how an algorithm's running time grows as input size increases. Big-O notation expresses the upper bound of that growth, like O(n) for linear time or O(log n) for logarithmic time, ignoring constant factors."},
    {"id": 66, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is the difference between BFS and DFS?", "answer": "Breadth-First Search (BFS) explores a graph level by level using a queue, good for finding the shortest path in unweighted graphs. Depth-First Search (DFS) explores as deep as possible along one branch before backtracking, using a stack or recursion."},
    {"id": 67, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is recursion?", "answer": "Recursion is when a function calls itself to solve smaller instances of the same problem, eventually reaching a base case that stops the recursion. It's commonly used for problems like tree traversal and divide-and-conquer algorithms."},
    {"id": 68, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is dynamic programming?", "answer": "Dynamic programming solves complex problems by breaking them into overlapping subproblems, solving each one once, and storing the result to avoid recomputing it — used in problems like the Fibonacci sequence or shortest path calculations."},
    {"id": 69, "category": "DSA", "question": "What is a hash table?", "answer": "A hash table stores key-value pairs and uses a hash function to compute an index for fast lookup, insertion, and deletion, typically achieving close to constant-time performance on average."},
    {"id": 70, "category": "Databases", "question": "What is a database?", "answer": "A database is an organized collection of structured data, stored and accessed electronically, typically managed by a Database Management System (DBMS) that handles storage, retrieval, and security."},
    {"id": 71, "category": "Databases", "question": "What is the difference between SQL and NoSQL databases?", "answer": "SQL databases (like MySQL, PostgreSQL) store data in structured tables with fixed schemas and use SQL for queries. NoSQL databases (like MongoDB, Redis) store data more flexibly — as documents, key-values, or graphs — and suit unstructured or rapidly changing data."},
    {"id": 72, "category": "Databases", "question": "What is normalization in DBMS?", "answer": "Normalization is the process of organizing database tables to reduce data redundancy and avoid inconsistencies, typically by splitting data into related tables connected through keys."},
    {"id": 73, "category": "Databases", "question": "What is a primary key vs foreign key?", "answer": "A primary key uniquely identifies each row in its own table. A foreign key is a field in one table that refers to the primary key in another table, used to link related data across tables."},
    {"id": 74, "category": "Databases", "question": "What is a JOIN in SQL?", "answer": "A JOIN combines rows from two or more tables based on a related column, letting you query data spread across multiple tables as if it were one. Common types include INNER JOIN, LEFT JOIN, and RIGHT JOIN."},
    {"id": 75, "category": "Databases", "question": "What is indexing in a database?", "answer": "An index is a data structure that speeds up data retrieval on a table by allowing the database to find rows without scanning every record, at the cost of some extra storage and slightly slower writes."},
    {"id": 76, "category": "Web Development", "question": "What is the difference between frontend and backend?", "answer": "Frontend is everything the user sees and interacts with directly in the browser — layout, styling, and interactivity. Backend is the server-side logic, databases, and APIs that power the application behind the scenes."},
    {"id": 77, "category": "Web Development", "question": "What is an API?", "answer": "An API (Application Programming Interface) is a defined set of rules that lets different software systems communicate with each other, such as a frontend app requesting data from a backend server."},
    {"id": 78, "category": "Web Development", "question": "What is a REST API?", "answer": "A REST API is an API that follows REST principles, using standard HTTP methods like GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE to operate on resources, typically exchanging data in JSON format."},
    {"id": 79, "category": "Web Development", "question": "What is the MERN stack?", "answer": "MERN stands for MongoDB, Express.js, React, and Node.js — a popular set of technologies used together to build full-stack JavaScript web applications, from the database to the frontend."},
    {"id": 80, "category": "Web Development", "question": "What is the difference between a framework and a library?", "answer": "A library is a set of reusable code you call when you need it, leaving you in control of the program's flow. A framework provides a structure that calls your code, dictating the overall flow of the application."},
    {"id": 81, "category": "Web Development", "question": "What is JSON?", "answer": "JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight, text-based format for representing structured data as key-value pairs, widely used for exchanging data between a server and a web application."},
    {"id": 82, "category": "Career & Exams", "question": "What companies hire B.Tech AI graduates?", "answer": "AI and ML graduates are hired by product companies, IT services firms, startups, and research labs across sectors like tech, finance, healthcare, and e-commerce, for roles such as ML engineer, data scientist, and AI researcher."},
    {"id": 83, "category": "Career & Exams", "question": "What is the GATE exam?", "answer": "GATE (Graduate Aptitude Test in Engineering) is a national-level exam in India that tests undergraduate engineering knowledge, used for admission into M.Tech programs and for recruitment into some public sector roles."},
    {"id": 84, "category": "Career & Exams", "question": "What is the importance of DSA for placements?", "answer": "Data Structures and Algorithms form the basis of most technical coding interviews at software companies, since they test a candidate's problem-solving ability and efficient use of computational resources."},
    {"id": 85, "category": "Career & Exams", "question": "What is a good final year project idea for B.Tech AI?", "answer": "Good projects solve a real problem and show end-to-end skills — examples include a semantic FAQ chatbot like this one, a disease prediction model, a recommendation system, a resume screening tool, or a computer-vision based attendance system."},
